# Code Style

## File Headers

- Always use `--!strict` at the top of every Luau file
- For performance-critical modules, add `--!native` and `--!optimize 2`
- Leave one empty line after headers before code begins

```luau
--!strict
--!native
--!optimize 2
```

## Line Length

- When editing lines that reach 80 characters, break them onto multiple lines
- Function parameters, long chains, and expressions should be split across lines
- Only apply this to lines being actively edited, not existing code

## Section Banners

- Use 30-dash banners on each side to separate major sections
- Common section order: Types → Constants → Algorithm/Utils → Class → Module

```luau
------------------------------ Section Name ------------------------------
```

## Naming Conventions

- Use camelCase for local functions, variables, and parameters
- Use PascalCase for module functions and class methods
- Prefix optional parameters with `_` (e.g., `_timeout: number?`), then normalize to local without prefix
- Use ALL_CAPS for true constants only

```luau
local function processData(
    value: string,
    _timeout: number?
): boolean
    local timeout = _timeout or 5
    -- ...
end
```

## Conventions

- Always type function parameters and return values—this enables inference everywhere else
- Don't redundantly annotate locals when the type is inferred (e.g., `local x = 3` not `local x: number = 3`)
- Use `T?` for optional types
- Use generics including `P...` and `R...` for variadic type packs
- Validate with `assert`; normalize optional `_args` to locals
- `pcall` callbacks; log errors with `warn()`
- Use `error("TypeName", 2)` pattern for assertion errors (level 2 points to caller)
- Freeze module tables and Class tables; optionally freeze `self`
- Use local functions to optimize for inlining
- Static helpers and singletons belong on the module table
- Always use `table.freeze()` for final module exports

## Documentation

- Use `--[[...]]` for multi-line docstrings above functions
- Include `@param` and `@return` descriptions for complex functions
- Keep comments concise; code should be self-documenting

```luau
--[[
    Validates and normalizes input data.
    @param value Input value to validate
    @param rules Validation rules to apply
    @return Normalized value or error
]]
local function validate(value: string, rules: {Rule}): Result
    -- ...
end
```

## OOP Pattern

For single-class modules, see canonical example:
`ReplicatedStorage/UserGenerated/Collections/LeftistHeap.luau`

For multi-class modules, prefix type names with the class name:
`ReplicatedStorage/UserGenerated/Concurrency/Bindable.luau`

### Type Structure

```luau
type Fields<self> = { ... }
type Functions<self> = { ... }
type PrivateFields<self> = Fields<self> & { ... }
type PrivateFunctions<self> = Functions<self> & { ... }

export type Type = Fields<Type> & Functions<Type>
type Private = PrivateFields<Private> & PrivateFunctions<Private>
```

For generic classes with variadic type packs:

```luau
type Fields<self, P..., R...> = { ... }
type Private<P... = ...any, R... = ...any> = 
    PrivateFields<Private<P..., R...>, P..., R...>
    & PrivateFunctions<Private<P..., R...>, P..., R...>
```

### Class Implementation

```luau
local Class = {} :: PrivateFunctions<Private>
local Metatable = table.freeze({ __index = Class })

-- Local functions for inlining, then assign to Class
local function Foo(self: Private, ...): T
    ...
end
Class.Foo = Foo

table.freeze(Class)
```

### Module Export

```luau
local function IsA(v: Type): boolean
    return type(v) == "table" and getmetatable(v :: any) == Metatable
end

local function Assert(v: Type): Type
    if not IsA(v) then error("<ClassName>", 2) end
    return v
end

local module = {}

function module.new(...): Type
    local fields: PrivateFields<Private> = { ... }
    local self: Private = setmetatable(fields, Metatable) :: any
    -- ...init...
    return self
end

module.IsA = IsA
module.Assert = Assert

return table.freeze(module)
```

## Type Safety

- Strive for zero type errors in every file for good static analysis
- Avoid `:: any` unless absolutely necessary (e.g., metatable assignment)
- Do not fix existing type errors unless explicitly asked

```luau
-- Only use :: any when required, such as complex setmetatable
local self: Private = setmetatable(fields, Metatable) :: any
```

## Game Logic

Focus on modular, reusable, and simple code:

- Break complex logic into small, testable functions
- Prefer clarity over micro-optimizations
- Keep functions focused on a single responsibility
- Use descriptive variable names over abbreviated ones

## Validation

For runtime type assertions, see `.cursor/rules/asserts.mdc`.

Especially important for networking—always validate data received from remotes.
